label: BODY

label: BODY

text: The composition of need-based spending differed by type of benefit, with the
label: BODY

text: Federal Government sharing the cost of medical care with States and localities to a
label: BODY

text: much greater extent than for other forms of need-based assistance.  Specifically, the
label: BODY

text: Federal Government paid 60 percent of the total cost of need-based medical care in
label: BODY

text: FY2004, but paid 89 percent of the cost of nonmedical benefits.  Medical care
label: BODY

text: consumed nearly 82 percent of all State and local need-based spending in FY2004,
label: BODY

text: but accounted for less than 46 percent of Federal need-based spending in that year.
label: BODY

text: An unduplicated count of beneficiaries in need-based programs is not
label: BODY

text: available.  During the 2002-2004 period, enrollment in TANF and food stamps
label: BODY

text: remained far below the peak levels of 1994-1995 (although food stamp enrollment
label: BODY

text: rose from the 2000-2002 period), while Medicaid enrollment set a record high.
label: BODY

label: BODY

label: BODY

text: The Census Bureau examined participation in major means-tested government
label: BODY

text: programs in 2004 (Census, 2006b).  It found that 25 million poor persons (two out
label: BODY

text: of three persons with pre-tax money income below the poverty threshold) lived in a
label: BODY

text: household that received some form of means-tested assistance that year.  More than
label: BODY

text: one-half of the poverty population (54 percent) was in a Medicaid-recipient
label: BODY

text: household.  More than one-third of the poor population (36.2 percent) lived in a
label: BODY

text: household that received food stamps; for means-tested cash assistance, the
label: BODY

text: proportion was 20.4 percent; and for subsidized or public housing, 16.1 percent.
label: BODY

text: Out of the total U.S. population (all income levels), the Census Bureau reported that
label: BODY

text: 26.4 percent lived in a household that received some form of major means-tested
label: BODY

text: aid in 2004 (Medicaid, 20.4 percent; means-tested cash assistance, 6.4 percent; food
label: BODY

text: stamps,  7.5 percent; and public or subsidized housing, 3.7 percent).
label: BODY

text: The CRS data series provides annual spending figures for 32 fiscal years
label: BODY

text: (1968, 1973, and 1975-2004), spanning a 36-year period of time.  Total
label: BODY

text: expenditures on cash and noncash need-based programs (including medical care
label: BODY

text: measured in constant 2004 dollars,1 grew at an annual rate of 5.4 percent between
label: BODY

text: 1968 and 2004.  However, the growth pattern was uneven.  Real spending almost
label: BODY

text: tripled in the first 10 years, declined in some years (1979, 1982, 1996, and 1997),
label: BODY

text: and in the last 7 years rose at an annual rate of 3.7 percent. Total per capita need-
label: BODY

text: based spending grew in real terms (constant FY2004 dollars) from $442 in FY1968
label: BODY

text: to a peak of $1,989 in FY2004.
label: BODY

text: When these trends are examined by type of benefit, the analysis is
label: BODY

text: dramatically different for medical spending versus nonmedical.  In constant
label: BODY

text: FY2004 dollars, spending for medical care grew at an average annual growth rate of
label: BODY

text: 7.2 percent between 1968 and 2004.  At the same time, real spending for
label: BODY

text: nonmedical forms of need-based assistance grew at an average annual rate of 4.1
label: BODY

text: percent.  Real spending for medical care increased in every year except 1982 and
label: BODY

text: 1996; spending for nonmedical care declined in 1980, 1981, 1982, and 1987, and
label: BODY

text: again in each of 1995 through 2000.  Total per capita spending for need-based
label: BODY

text: medical care grew from $132 in FY1968 to $1,100 in FY2004, while per capita
label: BODY

text: spending for nonmedical forms of need-based assistance grew from $310 to $889.
label: BODY

text: Table I-2 presents 1968-2004 Federal spending by form of benefit.  Measured
label: BODY

text: in constant 2004 dollars, Federal spending for all need-based benefits climbed from
label: BODY

text: $62.8 billion in fiscal year 1968 to $427.1 billion in fiscal year 2004, an increase of
label: BODY

text: 580 percent.  As the table shows, cash aid was the leading form of Federal need-
label: BODY

text: based spending until 1980, when it was overtaken in value by medical benefits.
label: BODY

text: Two years later, in 1982, Federal spending declined for all forms of need-based aid
label: BODY

text: except subsidized housing (because outlays reflected earlier commitments) and
label: BODY

text: education benefits.  In most subsequent years, aggregate real Federal spending for
label: BODY

text: need-based assistance steadily increased, except in 1986, 1996, and 1997.  Looking
label: BODY

text: at medical assistance only, Federal spending grew from $15.1 billion in FY1968 to
label: BODY

text: $194.8 billion in FY2004, for an increase of 1,190 percent.  Federal spending for all
label: BODY

text: other forms of need-based aid rose from $47.4 billion in FY1968 to $232.3 billion
label: BODY

text: in FY2004, for an increase of 390 percent.
label: BODY

text: Table I-3 shows that State and local spending for need-based benefits,
label: BODY

text: measured in FY2004 dollars, climbed from $25.9 billion in fiscal year 1968 to
label: BODY

text: $156.2 billion in FY2004, an increase of 502 percent.  Cash aid was overtaken by
label: BODY

text: medical benefits as the dominant form of State and local need-based spending in
label: BODY

text: 1976.  State and local spending rose steadily in all years after 1979, except for
label: BODY

text: 1993, 1996 and 2003.  Looking at medical assistance only, State and local spending
label: BODY

text: grew from $11.4 billion in FY1968 to $127.8 billion in FY2004, for an increase of
label: BODY

text: 1,025 percent.  State and local spending for all other forms of need-based aid rose
label: BODY

text: from $14.6 billion in FY1968 to $28.5 billion, for an increase of 195 percent.
label: BODY

text: Table I-4 shows total (Federal plus State and local) spending on need-based
label: BODY

text: benefits in FY2004 dollars.  Total spending rose from $88.8 billion in FY1968 to
label: BODY

text: $583.3 billion in FY2004; as noted earlier, this was an increase of 557 percent.
label: BODY

text: Aggregate spending rose in all years except 1979, 1982, 1996, and 1997.  Real
label: BODY

text: spending for medical benefits reached a new historic peak in fiscal year 2004.  For
label: BODY

text: other forms of benefits, however, peak spending took place in earlier years:  jobs
label: BODY

text: 1996; education, 2003; and services, 2003.  Looking at medical assistance only,
